        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Please see the PDF attachment Sect. 3 for further details.

As shown in Fig. 4 of the PDF attachment, we base our line sensitivity computation on the APEX 
spectrum of the 12CO(3-2) line, whose width is 4 km/s. For the spatial distribution of the flux, 
we consider that half of the total CO(3-2) emission comes from within the thermal infrared 
emission FWHM (0.7") measured by Jura et al. (2002). This corresponds to a flux density of 80 
mJy/beam for the selected 0.04" beam.

Our target sensitivity of 4 mJy is intended to give an SNR of 20 on the 12CO(3-2) line emission 
at the selected 0.2 km/s spectral resolution.

The stellar continuum flux is 62 mJy in ALMA band 7, from our modeling of the SED
(Fig. 3 in the PDF attachment), thus easily detected. The two stars will be slightly resolved
as the two stars are separated by approximately one ALMA resolution element.

We base our sensitivity computation on the continuum flux from the dust disk.
We use the Planck photometry of L2  Pup to estimate the emitted flux from the disk of
10^(-18) W/m2/micron, corresponding to 164 mJy in ALMA band 7.
At the requested angular resolution, this corresponds to 3.7 mJy/beam. We dedicate a spectral 
window to the observation of the continuum. The high SNR in the continuum will aid
calibration and alignment of the data sets.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The expansion velocity of the envelope of L2 Pup is 2 km/s in average (the CO(3-2) line width is 
4 km/s). We want to probe the keplerian motion in the disk. At the inner rim of the disk (6 AU) 
and considering a 2 Msun mass for the central object, we expect a +/- 20 km/s velocity. We also 
want to probe the inner cavity containing the central binary that may exhibit higher velocities.

The selected velocity resolution for the CO lines (0.2 km/s) is intended to give us a sufficient 
precision for the measurement of the gas velocity in the outer parts of the disk, where the 
velocity is of the order of 5 km/s. This velocity could be significantly less if our preliminary 
estimate of the star mass is too high.

The other selected lines (29SiO and HC15N) will be observed at a 0.5 km/s resolution. The SiO 
line may show higher velocities due to maser emission close to the AGB star (within about 2 
stellar radii from the photosphere).

Thanks to spectral averaging, we keep the data rate below 12 MB/s.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We want to observe L2 Pup in the 12CO J=3-2 and 13CO J=3-2 transitions to trace the kinematics
of the gas in the disk and the continuum emission, including at its inner rim, that is located
at a  radius of 0.1" (6 AU) from the central star. The outer radius of the dust disk is 0.2",
and we need 5 resolution elements over this dimension, hence our choice of angular resolution
(0.04").

The maximum angular scale that we need to sample is the extension of the dust disk that we 
determined from adaptive optics observations, corresponding to a diameter of 0.4" (13 AU).
For this  reason, we do not need the ACA and we request a single ALMA pointing.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
