        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The line width from the APEX observations presented in Fig. 4 of the PDF attachment is 4 km/s.

We expect that much of the bipolar structure velocity will exhibit small radial velocity
 components, due to the projection effect. Our hypothesis is that the dust disk collimates
the AGB wind along an orthogonal axis to the disk plane. In this framework, the high
inclination of the disk on the line of sight (82?, from our adaptive optics observations)
will result in a small projected radial velocity component that we want to sample properly.
Assuming a 10 km/s wind velocity, the radial component will be 10*cos(82?)=1.4 km/s only.
The selected 0.3 km/s resolution will therefore give 3 spectral resolution elements.

The data rate is kept below 12 MB/s.


</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We selected the angular resolution to resolve the typical scale of the bipolar cones (Fig. 2).
We also expect that large loops beyond the one observed in our infrared images may be present
in the envelope of L2 Pup.

The overall envelope of L2 Pup in the CO(2-1) line may extend up to a radius of 17" (modeling
by Winters et al. 2003). However, we are interested in the smaller spatial scales within this
envelope, up to approximately 5" in size, rather than the large scales of the smooth envelope. 

The orbital period of the inner binary system is expected to be a few years. However, as the
separation is only approximately 30 mas, we do not expect any significant variability on scales
of 0.2" or larger over the ALMA Cycle 3.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We base our sensitivity assessment on the CO(2-1) APEX single dish spectrum presented in Fig. 4
of the PDF attachment. The line width is 4 km/s and the intensity is 0.71 K. We considered
an efficiency of 0.6 for APEX, and a 12 m diameter for the conversion.

As for SG1, we consider that half of the CO line flux comes uniformly from the central 0.7"
around the star (according to the thermal IR observations by Jura et al. 2002).

Our target SNR is ~250 on the CO line emission (1.2 Jy/beam), so we request a 5 mJy sensitivity.
This sensitivity will allow us to probe the fainter extensions of the bipolar structure.

The continuum flux in ALMA band 6 from the star is 24 mJy, plus 48 mJy from the disk
(Fig. 3 of the PDF attachment). We base our sensitivity computation on the disk contribution,
giving 38 mJy per beam. The high SNR on the star's continuum will aid calibration
and alignment of the data sets.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
