    <prp:abstract>The final stages of stellar evolution involve fascinating physics, complex
chemistry and spectacular structures (disks, planetary nebulae,...).
The red giant L2 Pup is likely experiencing the early stages of the formation
of a planetary nebula. Its remarkable proximity (64pc) makes it the
second nearest AGB star.

VLT adaptive optics images revealed a dust disk seen almost edge-on, a close-in
companion and a compact bipolar structure. But these encouraging results
remain qualitative. We do not know the exact evolutionary state of the central
AGB star, neither its mass, and our interpretation in terms of bipolar
structure is currently based on its visible morphology only.

We will use ALMA to determine the stellar mass and the geometry of mass loss.
Our first science goal is to measure the rotation profile of the disk from the
CO(3-2) line to derive the mass of the central stars. This will enable us
to pinpoint the evolutionary state of the AGB.
Our second goal aims at testing the bipolarity hypothesis, by
mapping the velocity structure of the extended wind in the CO(2-1) line.
L2 Pup offers a unique vantage point on the disk-wind interaction.</prp:abstract>
